#
# umockdev-run CLI surface (decoded source-direct):
#   -d FILE  / --device=FILE          FILENAME_ARRAY (repeatable)
#   -i d=F   / --ioctl=devname=ioctlfilename
#                                     FILENAME_ARRAY
#   -p s=F   / --pcap=sysfs=pcapfilename
#                                     FILENAME_ARRAY
#   -s d=F   / --script=devname=scriptfilename
#                                     FILENAME_ARRAY
#   -u s=F   / --unix-stream=socket_path=scriptfilename
#                                     FILENAME_ARRAY
#   -e d=F   / --evemu-events=devname=eventsfilename
#                                     FILENAME_ARRAY
#   --version                         NONE (boolean)
#   program [args...]                 STRING_ARRAY positional
#
# GLib-auto-injected:
#   -h / --help                       built-in help
#   --help-all                        all help (including hidden)
#
# umockdev-run is the runner half of umockdev — a
# kernel-mock framework that LOADS device
# descriptions / ioctl dumps / pcap USB captures /
# evemu event files into a TESTBED, then runs a
# program under that testbed via LD_PRELOAD.
# Authored by Martin Pitt (Canonical; later Red
# Hat).  355 GH stars.  Sister tools in same
# project: umockdev-record (records real device
# state for later replay; uses GLib.OptionContext
# too; DEFERRED for separate round), umockdev-
# wrapper (helper script; bash, not Vala).
#
# Critical extraction note: umockdev-run uses
# **Vala `GLib.OptionContext`** at umockdev-run.
# vala:78 — corpus's **first documented Vala CLI
# library** + **first documented GLib OptionContext
# binding**.  GLib.OptionContext is the GLib C
# library's CLI parser (header `<glib/goption.h>`,
# implementation in `glib/goption.c`).  Used by
# nearly every GNOME C/Vala/Genie program — gtk-
# launch, gnome-settings-daemon, gnome-control-
# center, evolution, totem, rhythmbox, banshee,
# pitivi, brasero, etc.  Bound from C, Vala, Genie,
# Python (via GObject-Introspection PyGObject),
# JavaScript (GJS), Lua (lgi).  Distinct from R272
# C POSIX getopt (lower-level, no help/error
# generation), R305 C++ CLI11 (third-party single-
# header), R304 Ada GNAT.Command_Line (different
# postfix-marker syntax).  GLib.OptionContext is
# C-CALLER-FACING but FULLY GOBJECT-INTROSPECTED
# — every binding sees the same API.  Corpus's
# **first documented C-ABI-table-with-GObject-
# introspection CLI library**.  Extends cross-
# language CLI taxonomy to FORTY-SIX library
# variants: Rust (6), Go (4), Python (3), Crystal 1
# OptionParser (R269), Haskell (R270), OCaml (R271),
# C (R272), Java (R276), Kotlin (R277), Scala (R278),
# Dart (R279), Ruby (R280), Perl (R281), PHP (R282),
# Swift (R283), F# (R284), Lua (R285), C# (R286),
# Nim 1 parseopt (R287), Zig (R288), D (R289),
# Racket (R290), Common Lisp 1 (R291), Erlang (R292),
# Tcl (R293), Pharo Smalltalk (R294), Common Lisp 2
# clingon (R295), Julia (R296), SWI-Prolog optparse
# (R297), Pony stdlib cli (R298), Crystal 2 Admiral
# (R299), V stdlib `flag` (R300), Nim 2 cligen
# (R301), Clojure babashka.cli (R302), Gleam Glint
# (R303), Ada GNAT.Command_Line (R304), C++ CLI11
# (R305), Elixir Optimus (R306), **Vala GLib.
# OptionContext** (R307 — NEW).  **MAJOR PATTERN
# MILESTONE**: 46 cross-language CLI library
# variants documented.
#
# Critical extraction note: umockdev-run uses **Vala
# `OptionEntry[]` static struct-literal table** at
# umockdev-run.vala:41-60 — `const GLib.OptionEntry[]
# options = { {entry-1}, {entry-2}, ..., {null} };`
# is GLib's CANONICAL spec form.  Each entry is a
# 7-field struct literal: `{long-name, short-name-
# char, flags, OptionArg-enum, ref var, help-string,
# arg-placeholder-string}`.  The `{null}` sentinel
# terminates the table (C-style null termination —
# Vala's `OptionEntry[]` is bound to GLib's
# `GOptionEntry*` C array).  Distinct from R304
# Ada Define_Switch (positional method args), R305
# C++ CLI11 (chained method calls), R306 Elixir
# Optimus (keyword list).  GLib's approach: PURE
# DATA TABLE — the spec is a STATIC ARRAY of POD
# STRUCTS, parseable without any helper functions.
# Corpus's **first documented null-terminated-
# static-struct-table CLI pattern** — a C-ism
# preserved through to Vala via direct ABI binding.
#
# Critical extraction note: umockdev-run uses
# **GLib `OptionArg.FILENAME_ARRAY` for repeatable
# typed flags** at umockdev-run.vala:41 et seq —
# GLib's OptionArg enum has 6 main variants:
# `.NONE` (boolean), `.STRING` (single string),
# `.INT` (single integer), `.FILENAME` (single
# filename — UTF-8 vs locale handling distinct),
# `.STRING_ARRAY` (repeatable string), `.FILENAME_
# ARRAY` (repeatable filename), plus `.CALLBACK`
# (custom function).  Each `-d FILE` invocation
# APPENDS to the bound `string[]`.  Distinct from
# R303 Gleam Glint `strings_flag` (plural-suffix
# names the repeatable variant), R301 Nim cligen
# (auto-detected via `seq[T]`), R306 Elixir Optimus
# (`multiple: true` in option spec).  GLib's
# approach: ENUM-VALUE-DETERMINES-MULTIPLICITY —
# the SAME variable type (`string[]`) is bound
# regardless, but the OptionArg enum value tells
# the parser whether to store-or-append.  Corpus's
# **first documented OptionArg-enum-typed CLI
# parser pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: umockdev-run uses
# **GLib empty-string-name positional sentinel**
# at umockdev-run.vala:57 — `{"", 0, 0, OptionArg.
# STRING_ARRAY, ref opt_program, "", ""}` is the
# GLib CANONICAL way to capture remaining argv as
# positionals.  An OptionEntry with `""` long-name
# AND `0` short-name catches all NON-FLAG argv
# tokens into the bound `string[]`.  Distinct from
# R303 Gleam Glint `named_arg` (named-position),
# R304 Ada `Get_Argument` (stateful iterator), R306
# Elixir Optimus `args: [name: [...]]` keyword
# list, R305 C++ CLI11 (positional detected by
# no-leading-dash name).  GLib's approach: an
# EMPTY-NAME OptionEntry is the POSITIONAL CAPTURE
# SENTINEL.  Corpus's **first documented empty-
# string-as-positional-sentinel CLI pattern** — a
# convention rooted in the C-table's avoidance of
# special positional syntax.
#
# Critical extraction note: umockdev-run uses **Vala
# `[CCode (array_length=false, array_null_
# terminated=true)] static string[] opt_NAME;`
# C-ABI attribute on parser-bound variables** at
# umockdev-run.vala:23-35 — Vala's `[CCode (...)]`
# attribute controls how the Vala field is
# marshalled to/from C calling convention.  GLib's
# `string[]` (which is C's `char **`) is by default
# expected to carry an explicit length parameter,
# but GLib actually uses NULL TERMINATION (sentinel
# `NULL` at end).  The attribute tells valac:
# "this string[] is null-terminated, no separate
# length field".  Distinct from R304 Ada `aliased`
# (storage qualifier for pointer-of-variable), R305
# C++ CLI11 (template-deduced from reference type),
# R306 Elixir Optimus (no type annotation needed —
# dynamic).  Vala's approach: C-ABI ATTRIBUTES on
# the binding side, to match the C ABI of the
# underlying parser.  Corpus's **first documented
# C-ABI-attribute-on-binding CLI pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: umockdev-run uses
# **GLib `oc.parse (ref args)` mutating-argv
# parse-pattern** at umockdev-run.vala:82 — Vala's
# `ref` keyword passes the argv `string[]` BY
# REFERENCE; GLib MUTATES the array, removing
# parsed flags and leaving only positionals
# (CALLER MUST RE-READ args.length after parse).
# Distinct from R304 Ada Getopt(Config) (single-
# shot, no argv mutation — bindings get values),
# R305 C++ CLI11_PARSE macro (immutable argc/argv,
# parsed-values bound to struct fields), R306
# Elixir Optimus (immutable input, returns parsed
# tuple), R303 Gleam Glint (Result discriminated
# union return).  GLib's approach: ARGV-AS-MUTABLE-
# STATE — the same array is both input and output
# of parsing.  Common in C-style APIs.  Corpus's
# **first documented mutating-argv CLI parse
# pattern**.
